HEADWORD: adust
<hw>a*dust"</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧*d⟦ucr⟧st")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>adustus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>adurere</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>aduste</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Inflamed or scorched; dried
or darkened by heat.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The Libyan air
<xex>adust</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj> <au>AS</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Sunburnt.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark>
<au>AS</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A tall, thin man, of an <qex>adust</qex> complexion.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Looking or acting depressed;
atrabilious; gloomy.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <au>AS</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Adusted</ent>⟦br⟧
